<p> 
</p>
<p><b>Freedom of religion;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Minority issues;   
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Alleged imminent deportation of Jehovah&#8216;s Witnesses from Uzbekistan. 
According to the information received, Ms. Elena Tsyngalova and her two 
minor children were scheduled for deportation to Russia on Tuesday, 12 June 
</p><p>2012. On 5 September 2011, Ms. Tsyngalova was allegedly convicted for 
sharing her religious views as a Jehovah's Witness with an interested person. 
She was fined &quot;50 times&quot; the minimum wage. It was reported that on 6 
September 2011, the police searched Ms. Tsyngalova's apartment and seized 
religious literature regarding the Jehovah's Witnesses. She was again 
convicted and fined another &quot;50 times&quot; the minimum salary for possessing 
this religious literature. In early June 2012, she was allegedly summoned by 
the migration police who told her that she was to be deported on 12 June 
2012. To her knowledge, there has been no court hearing or any court 
decision ordering her deportation. The migration police told Ms. Tsyngalova 
that due to her alleged violation of Uzbek law by her &quot;illegal religious 
activity&quot;, they were revoking her residence permit and ordering her 
deportation. 
</p>
<p>21/08/2012 
 
 
 
 
 
