<p><b>Myanmar;  Torture;   
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Alleged violation of the fair trial and due process rights. According to the 
information received, Dr. Tun Aung, Chairman of the Islamic Religious 
Affairs Council in Rakhine State, Myanmar, was arrested on 11 June 2012 on 
charges related to communal violence in Rakhine State in early June. He was 
allegedly held incommunicado for three months. In September 2012, he was 
convicted and sentenced under the Foreign Exchange Regulation Act, 1947, 
Section 24 (1) to three years imprisonment. Since Dr. Aung&#8216;s initial arrest on 
11 June and throughout his subsequent trials, he has reportedly been denied 
the right to appoint a lawyer of his choice, instead being allocated a state 
lawyer whom he had not been allowed to meet privately. He has also been 
denied contact with his family. Dr. Aung suffers from a pituitary tumour and 
requires medication to manage this condition. In prison, he is not receiving 
the required medications. 
