<p><b>judges and 
</b></p>
<p><b>lawyers;  Iran;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Summary 
</b></p>
<p><b>executions;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Torture;   
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Alleged incommunicado detention, torture, unfair trial and sentence to death for 
moharebeh. According to the information received, on 26 January 2009, security 
forces arrested Mr Behrouz Alakhani, a 26 year old Kurdish citizen,  on charges of 
cooperation with the Party of Free Life of Kurdistan (PJAK) and participation in 
the murder of the Khoy Prosecutor. He was held incommunicado for 19 months 
before his transfer to Orumiyeh Central Prison, and was allegedly subjected to 
severe psychological and physical torture. During his detention, he was reportedly 
deprived of access to a lawyer and contacts with family members. In December 
2010, Mr Alakhani was brought before Orumiyeh Revolutionary Court, where he 
was sentenced to ten years imprisonment for possessing and transporting arms, and 
to the death penalty on charges of moharebeh, following a trial which violated 
procedural safeguards.  
</p>
